To build a Python wheel on Windows, do the following:

Prerequisites (install via Visual Studio 2022):
  - MSVC v143 C++ x64/x86 build tools
  - C++ Clang Compiler for Windows (clang-cl)
  - C++ Clang-cl for v143 build tools (x64/x86)
  - Git for Windows (provides bash.exe)
  - Python 3.12 (installed to C:\Python\Python312 or adjust paths below)
  - Bazel 8.5.1 (must match .bazelversion)


Step 1 — Set up environment. Copy and paste to PowerShell:

# Make sure clang-cl toolchain is on PATH and known
$env:BAZEL_LLVM = "C:\Program Files\Microsoft Visual Studio\2022\Professional\VC\Tools\Llvm"
$env:PATH       = "$($env:BAZEL_LLVM)\bin;$env:PATH"

# Remove global MSVC flags that might force 32-bit
Remove-Item Env:\_CL_ -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
Remove-Item Env:\CL   -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

# (Optional) if these exist, make sure they say x64
$env:VSCMD_ARG_TGT_ARCH = "x64"
$env:VSCMD_ARG_HOST_ARCH = "x64"


Step 2 — Build the wheel. Copy and paste to PowerShell:

bazel clean --expunge

bazelisk build //python/tflite_micro:whl.dist `
  --config=clangcl `
  --//python/tflite_micro:compatibility_tag=cp312_cp312_win_amd64 `
  --incompatible_enable_cc_toolchain_resolution=false `
  --action_env=BAZEL_LLVM="C:/Program Files/Microsoft Visual Studio/2022/Professional/VC/Tools/Llvm" `
  --action_env=PATH="C:/Program Files/Microsoft Visual Studio/2022/Professional/VC/Tools/Llvm/bin;$env:PATH" `
  --cxxopt=/Zc:__cplusplus `
  --linkopt=/MACHINE:X64 `
  --host_linkopt=/MACHINE:X64 `
  --features=-werror `
  --stamp --workspace_status_command="powershell -NoProfile -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File tools/workspace_status.ps1"

The output wheel will be in bazel-bin/python/tflite_micro/whl_dist/.

For other Python versions, replace cp312 with cp310, cp311, or cp313 in the
compatibility_tag value.

Tested with Bazel 8.5.1
